<font color="#FF0000">TEACHING ABOUT VIET NAM</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec 17 20:04:55 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I really hate to say this but the 'history' of NAM will end up being written from the various viewpoints already expressed here and the classes that teach that history will be taught from the viewpoint of the instructor.  Look carefully at American History as taught in Mississippi, Alabama, or Texas and that taught in Michigan, Wyoming or Vermont.  Do the Civil War portions even vaguely resemble one another?  The combat vets and the avoiders of every stripe and the active protestors and the passive protestors each have a viewpoint, each have an axe to grind in the writing and teaching of the 'history'.  Will the class taught by the protestors give the credit due to combat folks?  There is no way.  I served in the AF for 21 years -- from well before until well after the Viet Nam experience.  I lost friends there and I had family members declare C.O. status.  Even after reading most of the stuff in all this set of pages I have not changed my mind about this and I can't see that most others will change their minds either.  One hundred years from today not one of us reading this will care one way or the other.  <br><br>
I hope that those of you who are teaching this part of our history can be even handed, hope against hope actually.<br><br>
Good luck in your attempt.
